# translate-loop (`t`)

A small CLI for translating text, round-tripping it through another language,
capturing speech from your mic, and speaking results out loud. Installs a
single `t` command via pipx.

## Install

```sh
./install.sh
```

The script checks for `pipx` (and, on macOS, warns if `portaudio` is missing,
which is required for microphone capture), then runs `pipx install . --force`.

Manual install:

```sh
brew install pipx portaudio          # macOS; portaudio needed for `capture`
pipx install . --force
```

## Quick Example

Translate whatever you say in your microphone and say it out loud in the target language (`config.json`):
`t -t capture --say`

Translate whatever is copied into your buffer and say it out loud

## Configuration

On first run, `t` creates a global config at `~/.config/t/config.json`:

```json
{ "from": "english", "to": "russian" }
```

Precedence (later wins):

1. built-in defaults
2. global `~/.config/t/config.json`
3. local `./config.json` in the current directory (only keys you want to override)
4. `--from` / `--to` command-line flags

## Usage

```sh
t <text>
t --from <lang> <text>
t --to <lang> <text>
t --from <lang> --to <lang> <text>
t -t <text>                 # one-way mode (see below)
t --out <path> <text>       # also write result to file/dir
t --say <text>              # speak the result via macOS `say`
```

### `<text>` forms

`<text>` (a single token) is interpreted as:

- `buffer` → reads from the system clipboard
- `capture` → records from your microphone until you press Enter in the terminal,
  then transcribes via Google Web Speech using the `from` language
- a filepath (auto-detected; `./`, `../`, `/`, `~/` prefixes or an existing file)
  → reads the file contents
- anything else → literal text

Multiple tokens are always treated as literal text.

### Modes

**Default — round trip.** Translates `from → to → from` and prints the result
in the `from` language. This exposes translation drift (the "translate loop").

**`-t` — one way.** Translates `from → to` and prints the result in the `to`
language.

### `--out <path>`

Writes the printed result to the given path. If `<path>` is an existing
directory, writes to `<path>/t_output.txt`. Stdout still gets the result.

### `--say`

Pipes the result through macOS `say`, choosing a voice based on the result's
language (the `from` language in loop mode, `to` in `-t` mode). Falls back to
the system default voice if no mapping exists.

## Examples

Round-trip your clipboard through Russian and back to English:

```sh
t buffer
```

Speak a spoken English phrase as Russian:

```sh
t -t capture --say
```

Translate a file one-way into Spanish and save it:

```sh
t --to spanish -t ./notes.txt --out ./notes.es.txt
```

Override languages per-project with a local `config.json`:

```json
{ "from": "english", "to": "japanese" }
```

## How it works

- Translation: free Google Translate via
  [`deep-translator`](https://pypi.org/project/deep-translator/).
- Speech recognition: Google Web Speech via
  [`SpeechRecognition`](https://pypi.org/project/SpeechRecognition/) +
  [`PyAudio`](https://pypi.org/project/PyAudio/).
- Text-to-speech: macOS `say` (built-in, offline).
- Clipboard: [`pyperclip`](https://pypi.org/project/pyperclip/).

## Platform notes

`--say` and the default voice map target macOS. Everything else is
cross-platform, but microphone capture requires PortAudio (`brew install
portaudio` on macOS, `apt install portaudio19-dev` on Debian/Ubuntu).
